  mem_mono : ∀ s t, s ∈ Indep → t ⊆ s → t ∈ Indep := by
    intro s hs t ht
    simp [Indep] at hs ⊢
    obtain ⟨M, hM, hsM⟩ := hs
    refine ⟨M, hM, ?_⟩
    intro x hx
    apply ht
    exact hx
```

## Axiom 3: Independent sets satisfy the augmentation property

This is the key property for matroids. If $S$ and $T$ are matchable sets with $|S| < |T|$, then there exists an element $e \in T \setminus S$ such that $S \cup \{e\}$ is also matchable.

To prove this, we need to show that given two matchings $M$ and $N$ with $|V(M)| < |V(N)|$, there is an edge $e \in N$ not in $M$ such that $M \cup \{e\}$ is a matching.

This involves analyzing the symmetric difference of the two matchings. The symmetric difference will be a union of even-length cycles and paths. The endpoints of the paths in the symmetric difference are in $V(N) \setminus V(M)$. Since $|V(N)| > |V(M)|$, some vertex in $V(N) \setminus V(M)$ must be matched by $N$ but not by $M$. The edge corresponding to this vertex can be added to $M$.

```tactics
